		<br><div id="comment11459695" class="bgColor1"><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		  <td valign="top" width="60" align="center" class="borderClass" style="border: 0;"><div class="picSurround"><a href="/profile/ridojiri"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/userimages/thumbs/130236_thumb.jpg" vspace="4" border="0"></a></div></td>
		  <td class="borderClass" style="border: 0;" valign="top">
		  <div style="margin-bottom: 6px;"><a href="/profile/ridojiri">ridojiri</a> <small><span style="font-weight: normal;"> | 02-12-14, 12:28 AM</span></small></div>
		  Nearly all anime groups just sub because they enjoy doing so, and don't care what people do with their releases or subtitles or whatever- it means they are consuming the content after all. The few groups who do still care just hardsub (then again it's normally shit no-one cares about)- or they go by commission. <br />
<br />
Manga scanlation groups still have this hang up over dissemination of contents, watermarks, crediting the group, and so forth.<br />
<br />
I feel the difference is due to two major reasons, which are dependent on the nature of the mediums and transformative behaviours of the consumers. The first is that manga is in the vast majority read online instead of downloaded using files (there is still much anime streaming but the core community never does this- CR is also changing our behaviours). This changes the experience from being an investment - by adopting the work in a semi-permanent way onto a HDD - from a mere act of viewing. Files that are copies or ripoffs of a groups are very obvious and cannot be faked as simply as a manga scanlation. It's less interactive as such, not only because of the lack of sound and movement. The second reason is the community aspect in scanlations is much stronger. The process of bebinding and scanning a manga is a large investment, and the particular audience of a manga is usually more explicit and niche. There's an ethos behind the distribution of scanlations which isn't as accented for anime. The cleaning and translation and other parts also transforms the original source to something different, so there's a feeling of the group <em>producing</em> something instead of simply translating something.<br />
<br />
I don't know when the overall attitude for scanlation groups is going to change, if at all, but we are seeing at least precursors to scanlation groups not so hung up over their 'ownership' or 'crediting' of translations, such as '/a/nonymous translations' and more.<br />
<br />
</td>
		</tr>
		</table>
