		<tr>
		  <td valign="top" width="60" align="center" class="borderClass" style="border: 0;"><div class="picSurround"><a href="/profile/grifatmal"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/userimages/thumbs/1925076_thumb.jpg" vspace="4" border="0"></a></div></td>
		  <td class="borderClass" style="border: 0;" valign="top">
		  <div style="margin-bottom: 6px;"><a href="/profile/grifatmal">grifatmal</a> <small><span style="font-weight: normal;"> | 02-11-14, 10:44 PM</span></small></div>
		  I see your point and in general, I would agree with you. That's why a lot of groups include the mangaka, the publisher, the publication date as well as the ISBN when applicable on the credit pages, which are included with each release. If not, it is most often listed on their website. I think the teams are well aware that the work they do is trivial compared to what it takes to author and publish a manga. No question there. <br />
<br />
But in the context of this MALentine event, participants are asked to provide links to the MAL database entry of the source material. So author and publishers will get the credit that is their due. After that, it's a matter of proportion really. We, as scanlators, may not have done much, but if we did enough to make it more convenient/desirable for you to use the pages we worked on rather than the raw source material, shouldn't the groups get some kind of credit? It comes back to the notion of added value really. <br />
<br />
Idk either. We clearly are overthinking this. </td>
		</tr>
